column29: Physical description:Parchment, one leaf cut vertically in half.  Original measurement 313 x 255 (262 x 170) mm.; A, 313 x 130 (259 x 76) mm.; B, 305 x 127 (255 x 76) mm. B is creased and stained, and is slightly shrunken. 2 columns of 43 lines; ruled in lead point, double bounding lines. One extra line of text at the bottom of Av. Pricking visible on both inner and outer edge of leaf. Written above top line in an uneven romanesque textura script; black ink. A later hand has added “XIX” in left margin of Ar where Distinctio XIX begins.Decoration:Rubrics in red ink, 2-line initials in red, with decorative features but no penwork.  Guide letters visible in outer margins beyond pricking. Authors quoted are cited in the margins in red (Aug., Ber., etc.); two red dots in text show where quotations begin. New sentences marked by slightly decorative 1-line capitals in black ink, often minuscule forms writ large.Provenance:Written in England at the end of twelfth century, to judge from the script. Manuscript dismembered in England by the late 16th century and used to rebind the 1557 edition of Pico della Mirandola’s Opera (Basel: Henricus Petri 1557), employed as reinforcements of first and last quires. Physical traces include a vertical binding fold in what had been center of the leaf on each fragment, with holes for sewing on 5 bands on A and a piece of thread at the top right of Ar. Early modern English history of the printed book is not known. It belonged to the library of the Crozer Theological Seminary (founded 1867) of Bucknell University, Lewisburg, PA (book plate no. 208, q P58). Sold by Bucknell at Christie’s London, July 2003. Given to UCLA in 2005.
